    The Cystic Fibrosis Transmembrane Conductance Regulator (CFTR) anion
  channel is essential for epithelial salt\textendash water balance. CFTR
  mutations cause cystic fibrosis, a lethal incurable disease. In cells CFTR is
  activated through the cAMP signaling pathway, overstimulation of which during
  cholera leads to CFTR-mediated intestinal salt\textendash water loss. Channel
  activation is achieved by phosphorylation of its regulatory (R) domain by
  cAMP-dependent protein kinase catalytic subunit (PKA). Here we show using two
  independent approaches\textendash\textendash an ATP analog that can drive
  CFTR channel gating but is unsuitable for phosphotransfer by PKA, and CFTR
