  activation by PKA binding is completely reversible. Thus, PKA binding
  promotes release of the unphosphorylated R domain from its inhibitory
  position, causing full channel activation, whereas phosphorylation serves
  only to maintain channel activity beyond termination of the PKA signal. The
  results suggest two levels of CFTR regulation in cells: irreversible through
  phosphorylation, and reversible through R-domain binding to
  PKA\textendash\textendash and possibly also to other members of a large
  network of proteins known to interact with the channel.%
